            <div>
                <h3>What makes up The Sun?</h3>
                The Sun is mostly composed of helium and hydrogen at temperatures up to 27 million degrees Fahrenheit (15 million degrees Celsius). [<a href="#ref6">6</a>]<br>
                The inner layers of the sun are the core, followed by the radiative zone, and the convection zone. [<a href="#ref7">7</a>]<br>
                The outer layers of the Sun start with the photosphere as the innermost layer followed by the chromosphere, transition region, and then the outermost corona. [<a href="#ref7">7</a>]
            </div>

            <div>
                <h3>Why is The Sun important?</h3>
                The Sun itself is very important to life on Earth as it is the way that Earth is warmed which would make life impossible without it.<br>
                It is also an important part for plants on earth that need the energy from the Sun for photosynthesis.<br>
                The gravity of the Sun also keeps our planet in our solar system without it we would go flying into who knows where.
            </div>


